entry.title: Chinese Cultural Center (Wikipedia — did you know?)
entry.content: ... that Phoenix's Chinese Cultural Center (pictured) was remodeled into an ordinary office building over the objections of preservationists and community groups?

entry.title: 1977 World Snooker Championship (Wikipedia — did you know?)
entry.content: ... that John Spencer "exploded two myths" by winning the 1977 World Snooker Championship with a two-piece cue that he had only been using for a couple of months?

entry.title: Mansiya V. P. (Wikipedia — did you know?)
entry.content: ... that Mansiya V. P., an Indian classical dancer, has experimented with choreographing a fusion of classical Bharatnatyam and traditional Sufi music?

entry.title: southern corroboree frogs (Wikipedia — did you know?)
entry.content: ... that there are only around 30 southern corroboree frogs in the wild?

entry.title: man camps (Wikipedia — did you know?)
entry.content: ... that man camps can overwhelm local infrastructure, including emergency services, and contribute to an epidemic of violence against Indigenous women in North America?

entry.title: Abraham Hunt (Wikipedia — did you know?)
entry.content: ... that in 1776 Abraham Hunt entertained Hessian mercenaries with food and drink to render them incapable for duty the night before George Washington defeated them at Trenton?

entry.title: a historic watermill (Wikipedia — did you know?)
entry.content: ... that visitors to Balmaclellan in Scotland can stay in a historic watermill that is "remarkable" for the preservation of its internal workings?

entry.title: Itsuki Hirata (Wikipedia — did you know?)
entry.content: ... that Japanese mixed martial artist Itsuki Hirata's nickname is "Android 18" due to being told she looks like the Dragon Ball character?
